## Commit gate — mandatory for all UI changes

Do not commit until <!-- PARAMETERIZE: visual_confirmer_name --> visually confirms the change. Workflow:

1. Apply changes.
2. Start dev server.
3. Confirm clean build (no errors in startup output).
4. Tell <!-- PARAMETERIZE: visual_confirmer_name --> exactly what to look for and on which page.
5. Wait for visual confirmation.
6. Then commit (and push only if explicitly asked).

Claude is responsible for starting and running the dev server. <!-- PARAMETERIZE: visual_confirmer_name -->'s role is visual confirmation only.

<!-- OPTIONAL: globals_css_high_risk — include if has_design_system == true -->
`globals.css` is high-risk: a single unclosed brace or malformed value disables all styles on every page. Any session touching `globals.css` requires dev server confirmation before committing, even for one-line changes.
<!-- /OPTIONAL: commit_gate_section -->

## Session retros

At the end of every non-trivial session:

1. Check off completed Build-plan tasks and update `BACKLOG.md` (move resolved items out to a retro, not back into the file).
2. Write a retro to `docs/retros/YYYY-MM-DD-topic.md`. Template: `docs/retros/README.md`.
3. <!-- OPTIONAL: tooling_check_step --> Run `npm run check`, then commit and push including doc updates.

When <!-- PARAMETERIZE: visual_confirmer_name --> says **"end session"**, run the close-out without further prompts (the `/end-session` command codifies this exact sequence). When they say **"commit and push"**, run the same sequence but continue working after pushing.

At the start of a new session, read the most recent retro before doing anything else. This replaces asking <!-- PARAMETERIZE: visual_confirmer_name --> to re-explain what was last worked on.

## When BACKLOG outgrows the session-start read

`BACKLOG.md` loads every session, so it has a size budget. When it grows past a quick scan, split it into a thin one-line-per-item index, move each item's working detail into an on-demand `docs/tickets/<slug>.md`, and retire resolved items via `/end-session` (archive to `docs/tickets/archive/`, never delete). **Failure it prevents:** an always-loaded registry growing unbounded until it blows the session-start read budget and orientation gets expensive.

## Where new docs go

Default new `docs/` files into a typed subfolder by name; do not add to the root pile. **Failure it prevents:** root-level sprawl — with no routing rule every new doc lands loose at `docs/` (path of least resistance), so browsing the folder becomes a cognitive tax, and an artifact-emitting skill with no convention dumps its output at the repo root on run #1.

- **Stay at root** (anchors, frequently linked): `PRD.md`, `ARCHITECTURE.md`, `DECISIONS.md`<!-- OPTIONAL: decisions_active_anchor — include if include_decisions_active == true; inline content: `, `DECISIONS_ACTIVE.md` -->.
- **Route by name** into a subfolder (created lazily on the first file of that type): `*-brief.md` → `docs/briefs/`; `*-handoff.md` → `docs/handoffs/`; `*-reference.md` / domain notes → `docs/reference/`; research output → `docs/research/`; dated retros → `docs/retros/`; audits → `docs/audits/`.
- When writing inside a subfolder, use relative links at the correct depth (`../DECISIONS.md`) and re-check that cross-references resolve.

